type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.2.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.2.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.2.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-4.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="4.2.2.1" /> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="4.2.2.2" />, then:

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is a semi-simple abelian subcategory of the abelian subcategory of continuous families of Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, then its dual <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*]]></fr:tex> and the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\wedge ^p H]]></fr:tex> are also in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>;
        if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1,H_2\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Hom}(H_1,H_2)\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1252</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#253</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-253.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-4.2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> be a sub-object of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, in the category of continuous families of Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures.
      We will show that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> is a direct factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> in this category.
      We can suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to be homogeneous.
      If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex> is a polarisation form for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then the orthogonal of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex> with respect to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex> is indeed a sub-object of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> that is a supplement to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_1]]></fr:tex>.
      This proves (i)</fr:p>

    <fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> is of weight <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, then a polarisation of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> defines an isomorphism between <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes \mathbb {Q}(n)]]></fr:tex>.
      By <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.1.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="4.2.2.1" />, we thus have that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      For arbitrary <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, if we decompose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into its homogeneous components, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*=\bigoplus _n(H^n)^*]]></fr:tex>, whence again <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H^*\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      Finally, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\wedge ^p H]]></fr:tex> is a direct factor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigotimes ^p H]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Hom}(H_1,H_2)\simeq  H_1^*\otimes  H_2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
